THE RISK:
{
 "id": "prelet-lockout-year1-contestability",
 "title": "83% pre-let pipeline plus long-lead electrical frameworks leave almost no contestable Year-1 PDU orders",
 "narrative": "The obtainableFactor's own cross-check assumes DC electrical gear is locked 12–24 months before fit-out, which keeps a ≤2% Year-1 share plausible. But the FLAP-D development pipeline is 83% pre-let at a record-low 6.3% vacancy — the 2026–27 builds a new entrant would sell into had their electrical bill-of-materials specified inside framework agreements signed at pre-let, i.e. in 2023–24. The venture's first 12 months open onto a market where the visible demand is real but already awarded: what remains contestable is churn and expansion inside operating halls, a fraction of the 1% anchor. The YAM is not conservative; it is counting orders that were signed before the company existed in the market.",
 "category": "execution",
 "targetNodes": [
  "obtainableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "FLAP-D vacancy hits a record-low 6.3% with the pipeline 83% pre-let — capacity is committed to named tenants years before commissioning, and pre-let deals carry integrated electrical packages fixed at design lock",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-DE#c19",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "PDU line items ride those pre-let frameworks through the large-operator channel the venture targets first; RFPs that open during the venture's first 12 months are for capacity commissioning in 2028+, not for Year-1 revenue",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "digest:geo-DE#c19",
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The truly contestable Year-1 share of SAM sits below the 0.5% band floor; the 1% Prospeo anchor — already flagged as semantically fragile — overstates the first-year orderbook regardless of SAM size",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The 1% Year-1 benchmark reads as already-haircut — it is the bottom of the published 1–5% range, so it looks conservative. The pre-let statistic lives in commercial real-estate reports (JLL EMEA year-end), not in any PDU market report, so nobody on the team joins the two documents; the funnel has no 'already-awarded vs contestable' dimension where this could surface.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "Three or more CE colocation fit-outs commissioning in 2026–27 running open rack-PDU bake-offs (multi-bidder, no incumbent framework) during the venture's first two quarters.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.42,
  "rationale": "The 83% pre-let rate and record-low vacancy are documented for exactly the venture's window; offsetting this, retrofit, expansion and mid-market colo demand remains genuinely open, so total foreclosure is unlikely. [evidence revision: Trigger and framework-timing premises are strongly corroborated by independent industry sources, raising confidence in the foreclosure narrative. But the load-bearing leap — that rack-level PDUs (shorter lead time, often procured near fit-out and subject to churn/expansion demand) are foreclosed to the same degree as facility long-lead electrical gear — is not established by the evidence, which concerns transformers and switchgear. This keeps the likelihood near the original, marginally lower to reflect the unaddressed PDU-vs-facility-gear distinction that the hypothesis itself concedes leaves retrofit/expansion demand open.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.45
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.004,
   "note": "Contestable Year-1 share falls below the current 0.5% band floor once pre-awarded fit-out demand is netted out"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Share of CE data-center electrical/PDU procurements that are open multi-bidder vs sole-source or framework call-offs",
   "where": "TED (EU tenders portal) and major operator procurement portals (Digital Realty, Equinix, NTT supplier registration)",
   "threshold": "<20% of PDU line items contested openly over two quarters",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "FLAP-D pre-let percentage and vacancy in successive half-year prints",
   "where": "JLL EMEA Data Centre Report and Cushman & Wakefield EMEA updates",
   "threshold": "Pre-let stays above 80% with vacancy below 8%",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Map the 2026–27 CE commissioning pipeline project-by-project and audit whether each electrical package is already awarded or still open",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "note": "Converts the 0.5–3% band into a named-project contestable-demand figure"
  },
  {
   "action": "Re-aim the Year-1 motion at expansion and retrofit demand in operating halls and mid-market colo, where procurement is not pre-awarded at building pre-let",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  },
  {
   "action": "Pursue approved-vendor-list qualification inside at least one operator framework agreement so the venture is inside the wall when call-offs occur",
   "type": "contractual",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "EMEA year end data centre report 2025",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "JLL",
   "date": "2026-03-30",
   "excerpt": "FLAP-D vacancy hits record low of 6.3%, pipeline is 83% pre-let. Capacity is being absorbed faster than it can be replaced. Pre-commitment is now the only viable route to securing meaningful capacity across Europe.",
   "url": "https://www.jll.com/en-uk/insights/emea-data-centre-report",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data Center Electrical Procurement: Why the Order Has to Come Before the Design",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Build.inc",
   "date": "2026-06-22",
   "excerpt": "The conventional development sequence treats electrical equipment procurement as a downstream task... For data centers in 2026, that sequence is obsolete. Power transformer lead times from major manufacturers have reached 48 to 60 months.",
   "url": "https://build.inc/insights/data-center-electrical-procurement-sequence-workflow",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data centre vacancy hits record low as demand outstrips supply",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Estates Gazette",
   "date": "2026-04-09",
   "excerpt": "around 83% of space currently under construction already pre-let... pre-leasing now the primary route to securing capacity.",
   "url": "https://www.estatesgazette.co.uk/news/data-centre-vacancy-hits-record-low-as-demand-outstrips-supply/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.jll.com/en-uk/insights/emea-data-centre-report",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "FLAP-D vacancy hits record low of 6.3%, pipeline is 83% pre-let. Capacity is being absorbed faster than it can be replaced. Pre-commitment is now the only viable route to securing meaningful capacity across Europe."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://datacentrereview.com/2026/04/emea-data-centre-vacancy-hits-record-low-as-ai-demand-outpaces-supply/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "vacancy rates at the end of 2025 across the FLAP-D markets of Frankfurt, London, Amsterdam, Paris and Dublin fell to a record low of 6.3% in Q4 2025, down sharply from 16.9% in 2021. At the same time as the record-low vacancy rates, the data showed that 83% of the pipeline is already pre-let"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.estatesgazette.co.uk/news/data-centre-vacancy-hits-record-low-as-demand-outstrips-supply/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "around 83% of space currently under construction already pre-let, underlining the depth of occupier demand. This tightening supply-demand dynamic is reshaping how occupiers access space, with pre-leasing now the primary route to securing capacity."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://build.inc/insights/data-center-electrical-procurement-sequence-workflow",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The conventional development sequence treats electrical equipment procurement as a downstream task: finish design, secure permits, then buy the gear. For data centers in 2026, that sequence is obsolete. Power transformer lead times from major manufacturers have reached 48 to 60 months."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://feeds.deipower.com/blog/electrical-switchgear-shortage",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Medium-voltage switchgear lead times currently sit at 40-80 weeks, more than double pre-pandemic averages, while large low-voltage switchboards lag at 35-62 weeks compared to the 20-30 weeks once considered standard."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://gpuleaseindex.com/methodology/colocation-rfp-checklist",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "Organizations are increasingly evaluating multiple providers and financing models. Key factors include equipment availability, power efficiency, cooling requirements, and total cost of ownership."
  }
 ]
}

